reviewText: Riveting- couldn't stop watching. Saw the whole season in 3 days....

The first four seasons of Shameless were the most unexpectedly brilliant hours of television I've ever watched. Who knew that such an over-the-top and downright insane comedy could also have such heart and intelligence. Even after some questionable plotting decisions, I had faith in the writers to keep the quality going for at least a couple more seasons. Every show has an expiration date, but by the Season Four finale of Shameless, it seemed like the writers had a masterplan and that it could very well be the first Showtime series to stay great throughout its entire run.

Oh, how wrong I was.

Season Five is a dull, meandering mess that feels like a parody of its former self. The only plot-line that rang true was Kev and V's, but even that needed some serious trimming and did not merit a full season of build-up. But Fiona's story? Boring, predictable and counterproductive to her character development. Ian? Well, he's pretty much a new character now, but there's not much reason to care. Debbie? More teenage soap drama, rather than tapping into the character's loyalty and intelligence of past seasons. And don't even get me started on Lip...what a waste of Jeremy Allen White's talent.

But the biggest disappointment has to be Frank. Season Four, and its conclusion, would have you believe that Frank is going to change somehow. No, he'll never be a great parent or upstanding citizen, but some sort development was clearly order after he faced death and barely came out on top. But...no. They do NOTHING with Frank that we haven't already seen a better version of in prior seasons. More scamming, more antics. It's just so lazy.

Remember how crazy and energetic the first three seasons were? And then how tragic yet darkly comic Season Four was? Well, it seems like the writers couldn't make up their minds with Season Five. It's not as fun and awe-inspiring as the earlier episodes, and it's not as dramatically satisfying as Four. It's Shameless Lite, with an uncertain tone and a soap-opera structure.

What a shame.

I binge watched it and just finished the 4 seasons available.  I loved it.  Is 'disfunctional' a strong enough word for the Gallagher family?  Loved the kids, as their personalities developed, creating ways to deal with issues no kid should have to deal with at all.  They are all heroes in one way or another, all survivors.  Fiona and Lip, especially, although each of the others too.  Also loved the weird side stories, Sheila and her enormous dildos, then trying to adopt the Native American (ha!) kids, who selected her over their grandfather because she had WiFi, etc., etc.  Daughter Sammy and her weird fat kid, reveals another generation of 'trailer trash" but somehow still have heart.  Frank, the alcoholic druggie is another thing altogether.  A spectacular role for Macy but so painfully unsaveable; played well, I dislike his as much as the kids do but see his pride, his 'beat to another drummer' philosophy.

The great thing about the show is it is pretty close to what living on the southside is like. It also shows what living in poverty is truly about, and how hard it is to get ahead in life, yet it still teaches us that no matter what, you make the best of every situation regardless of what hand you were dealt! SPOILERS: Seasons 4 and 5 saw something pretty amazing begin and then, unfortunately, come to a grinding halt. The development of Noel Fisher's character Mickey Milkovich was dynamic, profound, and heart-rending. When you consider how little screen time Mickey had overall, it's even more astonishing. Still true to the Shameless brand, there are enough hilarious moments to keep this show teetering between comedy and tragedy, but few of the characters really grow in positive directions. Mickey was the exception (as was Sheilah). If you found Mickey's storyline as engrossing as I did, you too will want to replay the season 5 finale just to appreciate the subtle and potent non-verbal poetry of Fisher's performance (think: running down the sidewalk). Unfortunately (and this is the SPOILER), the arc of Mickey's development was really just cresting when the actor who played him opted out of the show. His scene in the Season 6 opener is gut wrenching. Really good stuff. Hard to see it come to an end.
